 {"id":"frankenjax-h8l2","title":"Fix large I64 precision loss in sort and argsort","description":"Review finding [HIGH]. In crates/fj-lax/src/tensor_ops.rs, sort_along_axis currently converts integral tensor elements to f64 before sorting (lines around 2589 and 2611-2639). Values above 2^53 cannot be represented exactly as f64, so Sort can silently rewrite distinct I64 literals when it casts the sorted f64 back to i64, and Argsort can compare rounded values instead of the original integer keys.\n\nReproduction to add as a failing test: evaluate Primitive::Sort on an I64 tensor [9007199254740993, 9007199254740992]. Expected exact sorted values are [9007199254740992, 9007199254740993], but the current implementation routes both values through f64 and can collapse/corrupt the larger literal. Also evaluate Primitive::Argsort on [9007199254740993, 9007199254740992, 9007199254740994] and assert the indices reflect true i64 ordering, not f64-rounded ordering.\n\nSuggested fix: sort integral tensors with an i64 key path that preserves the original Literal for Sort and uses the same exact key for Argsort. Keep the f64 total_cmp path for floating tensors so NaN ordering remains covered by existing tests. Validate with rch cargo test -p fj-lax sort and rch cargo test -p fj-conformance --test sort_oracle.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-29T00:48:32.434847663Z","created_by":"cod_2_reviewer","updated_at":"2026-04-29T01:02:03.945725637Z","closed_at":"2026-04-29T01:02:03.942929667Z","close_reason":"Fixed exact integer sort and argsort ordering with oracle regressions","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}

